WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.500 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.870 align:middle line:84%
>>With the price of energy and
gas inching skyward by the day,

00:00:03.870 --> 00:00:05.600 align:middle line:84%
it seems that we're
finally motivated

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:07.620 align:middle line:84%
to look at the
alternatives, as witnessed

00:00:07.620 --> 00:00:10.900 align:middle line:84%
by the six-month to one
year wait for hybrid cars.

00:00:10.900 --> 00:00:14.170 align:middle line:84%
Fortunately, some people have
been ahead of the game, decades

00:00:14.170 --> 00:00:14.980 align:middle line:90%
ahead.

00:00:14.980 --> 00:00:17.280 align:middle line:84%
Reinhold Ziegler is
one of those people

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:19.000 align:middle line:84%
who has made it
his life to develop

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.720 align:middle line:84%
non-polluting renewable energy
sources for both domestic use

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:23.560 align:middle line:90%
and abroad.

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:26.570 align:middle line:84%
As you'll learn, the US
is way behind the curve

00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:29.780 align:middle line:84%
because it seems that we only
respond to crisis before we're

00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:31.010 align:middle line:90%
willing to change.

00:00:31.010 --> 00:00:32.670 align:middle line:90%
But better late than never.

00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:43.290 align:middle line:90%


00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:47.430 align:middle line:84%
Let's begin with talking
to you a little bit

00:00:47.430 --> 00:00:50.310 align:middle line:84%
about your historical
path that has gotten you

00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:53.304 align:middle line:84%
to this point of becoming
a renewable energy expert.

00:00:53.304 --> 00:00:55.000 align:middle line:90%
>>Mm-hm.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.270 align:middle line:84%
Well, essentially it
started for me-- I

00:00:58.270 --> 00:01:05.190 align:middle line:84%
was a science major, physics
engineering major in college,

00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:09.690 align:middle line:84%
and I really couldn't quite
figure out at the time

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:11.580 align:middle line:84%
why I was solving
all these problems.

00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:14.350 align:middle line:84%
It seemed like I was the biggest
problem that I had to work on.

00:01:14.350 --> 00:01:23.540 align:middle line:84%
So we did a lot of initial work
with conventional engineering

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:27.220 align:middle line:84%
projects, and then I met a
group of people in Berkeley

00:01:27.220 --> 00:01:33.050 align:middle line:84%
and we began to put together
the first Integral Urban House.

00:01:33.050 --> 00:01:38.220 align:middle line:84%
This is the Farallones
Institute 1976, '77.

00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:40.610 align:middle line:84%
And so we put together a
house that was completely

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:42.240 align:middle line:90%
powered by the sun the wind.

00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:46.867 align:middle line:84%
And we had a beehive
in the building

00:01:46.867 --> 00:01:49.200 align:middle line:84%
that the bees would fly out
to the rest of neighborhood,

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:51.935 align:middle line:84%
collect all the honey,
bring it back to our house.

00:01:51.935 --> 00:01:54.650 align:middle line:90%


00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:58.520 align:middle line:84%
We'd have gardens,
biodynamic gardens.

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:01.120 align:middle line:84%
We'd have integrated
pest management.

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:02.840 align:middle line:84%
So if there were
any aphids, we'd

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:07.146 align:middle line:84%
bring in ladybugs who would
get rid of the aphids.

00:02:07.146 --> 00:02:13.530 align:middle line:84%
And just-- where there was
concrete, we had strawberries.

00:02:13.530 --> 00:02:16.140 align:middle line:84%
It was the first time
that we had put together

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:19.390 align:middle line:84%
all the talent of creating
a house that was completely

00:02:19.390 --> 00:02:22.410 align:middle line:84%
self-reliant, powered
by the sun and the wind,

00:02:22.410 --> 00:02:24.700 align:middle line:84%
with fish growing in the
backyard and chickens

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:27.370 align:middle line:84%
in the chicken
coops, and rabbits.

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:30.300 align:middle line:84%
And so, it created
a collaboration

00:02:30.300 --> 00:02:32.480 align:middle line:84%
that has been going
on for around 25 years

00:02:32.480 --> 00:02:38.220 align:middle line:84%
now to build self-sustaining
life support systems.

00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:41.350 align:middle line:84%
And there's a tremendous
amount of good news

00:02:41.350 --> 00:02:43.420 align:middle line:90%
coming from that work.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:45.850 align:middle line:84%
>>So here we are, almost
30 years down the road

00:02:45.850 --> 00:02:50.020 align:middle line:84%
from that time, and
now your backyard

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:54.990 align:middle line:84%
has stretched overseas to doing
very large joint endeavors

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:57.780 align:middle line:90%
with the Chinese even.

00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:58.400 align:middle line:90%
>>Mm-hm.

00:02:58.400 --> 00:03:04.190 align:middle line:84%
>>And so between those
two points in history,

00:03:04.190 --> 00:03:08.555 align:middle line:84%
tell me about the evolution
of some of these technologies

00:03:08.555 --> 00:03:11.220 align:middle line:84%
that you were working
with back in 1976,

00:03:11.220 --> 00:03:13.092 align:middle line:84%
and where they are
today, and how close

00:03:13.092 --> 00:03:14.300 align:middle line:90%
they are to being rolled out.

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:18.784 align:middle line:84%
It would seem that 30
years is a long time.

00:03:18.784 --> 00:03:20.200 align:middle line:84%
Logically, it seems
that we should

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:23.430 align:middle line:84%
be seeing some of
this in use right now.

00:03:23.430 --> 00:03:25.370 align:middle line:90%
But we're not.

00:03:25.370 --> 00:03:27.866 align:middle line:90%
>>It's definitely emerged.

00:03:27.866 --> 00:03:31.950 align:middle line:84%
