of the components of it.

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:37.820 align:middle line:84%
Certainly, photovoltaics,
which was about $1,000 a watt

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:39.020 align:middle line:90%
in 1976.

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:41.990 align:middle line:84%
>>This is solar power
you're talking about?

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:44.750 align:middle line:84%
>>Electricity from
direct sunlight

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:46.080 align:middle line:90%
was used for satellites.

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.380 align:middle line:84%
It was very expensive
at that time.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:52.380 align:middle line:84%
Over the years, we've
had major breakthroughs

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:54.570 align:middle line:84%
to where now the
cost of photovoltaics

00:03:54.570 --> 00:03:56.840 align:middle line:90%
is down at around $3 a watt.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.250 align:middle line:90%
From $1,000 a watt to $3 a watt.

00:03:59.250 --> 00:04:01.254 align:middle line:84%
>>Then why aren't we
seeing more of it?

00:04:01.254 --> 00:04:03.837 align:middle line:84%
Or is that a separate question
we should get into a little bit

00:04:03.837 --> 00:04:04.450 align:middle line:90%
later?

00:04:04.450 --> 00:04:06.650 align:middle line:84%
>>We are definitely
seeing more of it,

00:04:06.650 --> 00:04:07.985 align:middle line:90%
and I will provide you examples.

00:04:07.985 --> 00:04:11.000 align:middle line:90%


00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.090 align:middle line:84%
A lot of the states have
provided incentive programs

00:04:14.090 --> 00:04:17.540 align:middle line:84%
to buy down the cost
of photovoltaics.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:21.490 align:middle line:84%
California, Nevada,
Texas, New York,

00:04:21.490 --> 00:04:24.190 align:middle line:84%
if you buy a photovoltaic
power system,

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:28.190 align:middle line:84%
