00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:36.050 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of farmers
who, at that time,

00:11:36.050 --> 00:11:41.517 align:middle line:84%
had small wind generators on
their farms got a hook up.

00:11:41.517 --> 00:11:42.850 align:middle line:90%
They thought, oh, this is great.

00:11:42.850 --> 00:11:45.930 align:middle line:84%
We'll get a washing machine,
the wife will like that.

00:11:45.930 --> 00:11:50.800 align:middle line:84%
I'll have some electricity for
threshing machines, toasters,

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:53.273 align:middle line:84%
and the radio, of
course, which was

00:11:53.273 --> 00:11:56.740 align:middle line:84%
sort of the main cultural
piece in the house,

00:11:56.740 --> 00:11:58.160 align:middle line:90%
and they began to get hooked up.

00:11:58.160 --> 00:12:01.790 align:middle line:84%
And so the irony of the
story is in many cases,

00:12:01.790 --> 00:12:04.150 align:middle line:84%
and we've interviewed
these farmers,

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:06.070 align:middle line:84%
they would say that after
they were hooked up,

00:12:06.070 --> 00:12:09.344 align:middle line:84%
the REA would come
back and say, listen,

00:12:09.344 --> 00:12:11.510 align:middle line:84%
now that you're hooked up
to civilization you really

00:12:11.510 --> 00:12:14.220 align:middle line:84%
won't need that wind
generator anymore.

00:12:14.220 --> 00:12:17.050 align:middle line:84%
Why don't you knock
it off it's towers?

00:12:17.050 --> 00:12:21.070 align:middle line:90%
Why don't you-- or take it down.

00:12:21.070 --> 00:12:23.694 align:middle line:84%
And then they would say, well,
we kind of like it, you know.

00:12:23.694 --> 00:12:25.860 align:middle line:84%
They say, well, you're not
going to need it anymore.

00:12:25.860 --> 00:12:29.460 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of machines, I
would say tens of thousands

00:12:29.460 --> 00:12:31.970 align:middle line:84%
of machines, were
taken off their tower

00:12:31.970 --> 00:12:34.400 align:middle line:84%
or knocked off
the tower and laid

00:12:34.400 --> 00:12:37.430 align:middle line:84%
in those fields
for some 30 years

00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:40.370 align:middle line:84%
until the '70s, when
we went back out there

00:12:40.370 --> 00:12:43.300 align:middle line:84%
and bought the Jacobs
generators, which

00:12:43.300 --> 00:12:47.000 align:middle line:84%
were like the Cadillac of
wind machines at that time.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:51.030 align:middle line:84%
And then in the late '70s,
we began to refurbish those.

00:12:51.030 --> 00:12:53.920 align:middle line:84%
And our group actually,
we had the privilege

00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:56.720 align:middle line:84%
of working with the
Jacobs brothers, who

00:12:56.720 --> 00:13:01.300 align:middle line:84%
taught us everything they
knew as we began to make wind

00:13:01.300 --> 00:13:05.450 align:middle line:84%
powered alternators, A/C
generating alternators.

00:13:05.450 --> 00:13:09.970 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of what we learned
came from the Jacobs brothers.

00:13:09.970 --> 00:13:14.730 align:middle line:84%
>>So you made a business of
recovering these old machines

00:13:14.730 --> 00:13:17.490 align:middle line:84%
and then, like you say,
refurbishing them and then

00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:20.370 align:middle line:84%
putting them back up in--
where were they utilized?

00:13:20.370 --> 00:13:22.840 align:middle line:84%
Were they used primarily
in-- did you bring them back

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:26.200 align:middle line:84%
to California or where
were they utilized?

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:29.750 align:middle line:84%
>>We had a factory in
Berkeley, Aero Power Systems,

00:13:29.750 --> 00:13:33.430 align:middle line:84%
and we did renovate
the machines.

00:13:33.430 --> 00:13:36.340 align:middle line:84%
We also immediately went on
to some of the breakthroughs

00:13:36.340 --> 00:13:38.300 align:middle line:90%
that have happened.

00:13:38.300 --> 00:13:40.370 align:middle line:84%
These were generators
so they had brushes,

00:13:40.370 --> 00:13:43.580 align:middle line:84%
which had to be re-machined,
and so we went on

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:47.340 align:middle line:84%
to creating new aluminum
castings for alternators, which

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:50.770 align:middle line:84%
are A/C producing
alternating current

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:52.130 align:middle line:90%
that have electronic circuits.

00:13:52.130 --> 00:13:56.030 align:middle line:84%
So we were the first to
use modern voltage control

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:58.400 align:middle line:90%
circuits on these generators.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:03.180 align:middle line:84%
And also had an extensive blade
company and blade manufacturer,

00:14:03.180 --> 00:14:08.560 align:middle line:84%
so we redo the governors
and the blade assemblies

00:14:08.560 --> 00:14:12.870 align:middle line:84%
for harnessing the
energy in the wind.

00:14:12.870 --> 00:14:15.600 align:middle line:84%
>>Before we go on to
what's happened since then,

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:18.430 align:middle line:84%
because the new
technology in wind power

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:23.510 align:middle line:84%
looks considerably different
from the old windmills,

00:14:23.510 --> 00:14:25.480 align:middle line:84%
let's talk about
some other modalities

00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:28.090 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll come back to
the advances in the technology.

00:14:28.090 --> 00:14:29.464 align:middle line:84%
We've talked about
photovoltaics,

00:14:29.464 --> 00:14:33.090 align:middle line:84%
we've talked about wind,
what about tidal power

00:14:33.090 --> 00:14:35.270 align:middle line:90%
from the ocean's waves?

00:14:35.270 --> 00:14:37.010 align:middle line:90%
>>Sure.

00:14:37.010 --> 00:14:41.240 align:middle line:84%
It turns out that water is
800 times as dense as air.

00:14:41.240 --> 00:14:44.500 align:middle line:84%
So in a machine, a wind
machine-- if you placed a wind

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:46.830 align:middle line:84%
machine in a river,
for example, you

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:50.090 align:middle line:84%
would get effectively
25 times the output as

00:14:50.090 --> 00:14:51.710 align:middle line:90%
if it was in the wind.

00:14:51.710 --> 00:14:54.340 align:middle line:90%
That's an effective output.

00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:58.990 align:middle line:84%
So a little 500 watt
wind machine in the water

00:14:58.990 --> 00:15:03.370 align:middle line:90%
would produce 12,500 watts.

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:06.170 align:middle line:90%
And we've documented that.

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:10.420 align:middle line:84%
So certainly, current turbines
are extremely attractive.

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:13.680 align:middle line:84%
There are a variety of formats
being tested and tried right

00:15:13.680 --> 00:15:19.610 align:middle line:84%
now, a lot of them in England--
radioactivity in England.

00:15:19.610 --> 00:15:21.420 align:middle line:84%
And there's some
talk in the Bay Area

00:15:21.420 --> 00:15:26.330 align:middle line:84%
of harnessing the tidal flows
that flow underneath the Golden

00:15:26.330 --> 00:15:29.760 align:middle line:90%
Gate Bridge, and its massive.

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:35.200 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the energy in the water
could power all of our energy

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:38.990 align:middle line:90%
needs several times over.

00:15:38.990 --> 00:15:40.520 align:middle line:84%
>>Has this technology
been developed

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:44.770 align:middle line:90%
to the point of usefulness?

00:15:44.770 --> 00:15:45.270 align:middle line:90%
>>Yeah.

00:15:45.270 --> 00:15:46.156 align:middle line:90%
>>Is it already there?

00:15:46.156 --> 00:15:46.781 align:middle line:90%
Is it patented?

00:15:46.781 --> 00:15:47.890 align:middle line:90%
Is it ready to go?

00:15:47.890 --> 00:15:49.080 align:middle line:90%
>>There are patents.

00:15:49.080 --> 00:15:52.720 align:middle line:84%
There have been demonstration
projects over the years,

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:55.420 align:middle line:90%
both in the Hudson River.

00:15:55.420 --> 00:15:59.490 align:middle line:84%
There been some attempts
to harness the Gulf Stream.

00:15:59.490 --> 00:16:02.560 align:middle line:90%
Several river experiments.

00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:05.380 align:middle line:84%
My first information on
this came from a project

00:16:05.380 --> 00:16:08.480 align:middle line:84%
to harness the Nile,
to basically pump

00:16:08.480 --> 00:16:09.600 align:middle line:90%
water over the Nile.

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:14.140 align:middle line:84%
To use an underwater wind
machine, water machine,

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:18.860 align:middle line:84%
to lift water over the
dyke into the Sudan.

00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:20.390 align:middle line:84%
So those-- it's
been accomplished.

00:16:20.390 --> 00:16:22.560 align:middle line:84%
And what it's coming
down to now is

00:16:22.560 --> 00:16:25.500 align:middle line:84%
what is the right
economy of scale,

00:16:25.500 --> 00:16:32.390 align:middle line:84%
and should we harness
water directly?

00:16:32.390 --> 00:16:35.305 align:middle line:84%
Because it is a
tremendous thrust force.

00:16:35.305 --> 00:16:39.780 align:middle line:84%
The weight of the water, the
mass of that flowing water

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:42.340 align:middle line:84%
can overturn any
kind of structure.

00:16:42.340 --> 00:16:48.420 align:middle line:84%
So we've been looking at using
compressed air, for example.

00:16:48.420 --> 00:16:51.700 align:middle line:84%
Creating underwater
venturis and creating-- I

00:16:51.700 --> 00:16:54.700 align:middle line:84%
mean the air be drawn
into some air turbines

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:57.439 align:middle line:84%
as an easier way
of dealing with it.

00:16:57.439 --> 00:16:59.480 align:middle line:84%
The machine that I've been
working with basically

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:02.410 align:middle line:84%
uses hydraulics, so we have
no electricity under water,

00:17:02.410 --> 00:17:04.839 align:middle line:90%
everything is above water.

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:06.650 align:middle line:84%
But we're creating
hydraulic pressure,

00:17:06.650 --> 00:17:10.930 align:middle line:84%
which then runs hydraulic
motors and hydraulic generation

00:17:10.930 --> 00:17:13.710 align:middle line:90%
of electricity.

00:17:13.710 --> 00:17:16.394 align:middle line:84%
>>So now let's go
on to another issue,

00:17:16.394 --> 00:17:17.810 align:middle line:84%
because we're
just-- we're looking

00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:19.110 align:middle line:90%
at the needs of the future.

00:17:19.110 --> 00:17:22.700 align:middle line:84%
We're going to need
clean renewable energy.

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:27.640 align:middle line:84%
We have major issues with the
environment and the greenhouse

00:17:27.640 --> 00:17:32.260 align:middle line:84%
effect, et cetera, so we need
a clean source of energy.

00:17:32.260 --> 00:17:36.610 align:middle line:84%
We're looking at wind, we're
looking at hydraulic power.

00:17:36.610 --> 00:17:37.470 align:middle line:90%
What do you call it?

00:17:37.470 --> 00:17:38.330 align:middle line:90%
Tidal power?

00:17:38.330 --> 00:17:41.220 align:middle line:84%
What is the term for this
whole genre of technology?

00:17:41.220 --> 00:17:41.830 align:middle line:90%
Tidal power?

00:17:41.830 --> 00:17:42.330 align:middle line:90%
>>Yeah.

00:17:42.330 --> 00:17:45.570 align:middle line:84%
It's tidal power
or current turbines

00:17:45.570 --> 00:17:50.130 align:middle line:84%
or hydropower, which is
where you would lift water

00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:52.830 align:middle line:84%
or accumulate
water behind a dam.

00:17:52.830 --> 00:17:57.112 align:middle line:84%
And there are now better
solutions than building dams,

00:17:57.112 --> 00:17:58.570 align:middle line:84%
because the result
of building dams

00:17:58.570 --> 00:18:03.840 align:middle line:84%
is you lay waste to a tremendous
amount of land behind the dam.

00:18:03.840 --> 00:18:09.160 align:middle line:84%
We now can do ambient
turbines that are in rivers

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:12.330 align:middle line:84%
and extract the water
out of the river,

00:18:12.330 --> 00:18:14.750 align:middle line:84%
run it through a turbine,
put it back into the river.

00:18:14.750 --> 00:18:17.850 align:middle line:84%
We're just removing
the energy of that.

00:18:17.850 --> 00:18:21.850 align:middle line:84%
And hydropower is, in
effect, gravity energy.

00:18:21.850 --> 00:18:23.850 align:middle line:90%
It's based on the gravity.

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:26.640 align:middle line:84%
>>So we're looking at power
sources through the sun,

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:29.740 align:middle line:90%
through the wind, through water.

00:18:29.740 --> 00:18:33.380 align:middle line:84%
Another issue is becoming
fresh water supplies,

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:35.900 align:middle line:90%
clean and fresh water supplies.

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:37.870 align:middle line:90%
Globally this is an issue.

00:18:37.870 --> 00:18:42.310 align:middle line:84%
What about progress in the area,
for example, of desalinization?

00:18:42.310 --> 00:18:44.270 align:middle line:90%
>>Mm-hm.

00:18:44.270 --> 00:18:45.430 align:middle line:90%
Certainly.

00:18:45.430 --> 00:18:48.600 align:middle line:84%
I would also mention
one more energy source

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:52.750 align:middle line:84%
that is equally
interesting and important,

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:56.500 align:middle line:84%
and that is the internal
combustion engine.

00:18:56.500 --> 00:19:02.190 align:middle line:84%
We now have fuels that
are incredibly clean.

00:19:02.190 --> 00:19:03.850 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it involves
combustion, which

00:19:03.850 --> 00:19:05.570 align:middle line:84%
is what we're trying
to get away from,

00:19:05.570 --> 00:19:08.560 align:middle line:84%
but we now have
biodiesel, for example.

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:10.821 align:middle line:84%
>>Can you talk about
biodiesel for a moment?

00:19:10.821 --> 00:19:11.320 align:middle line:90%
>>Certainly.

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:15.020 align:middle line:84%
Biodiesel allows
us to make diesel

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:20.610 align:middle line:84%
from biomass, which can grow on
the millions of acres of land

00:19:20.610 --> 00:19:22.401 align:middle line:90%
that are just being unutilized.

00:19:22.401 --> 00:19:24.150 align:middle line:84%
When you drive through
the west some time,

00:19:24.150 --> 00:19:28.480 align:middle line:84%
you just drive-through millions
of acres of unused land.

00:19:28.480 --> 00:19:37.530 align:middle line:84%
We could easily plant canola,
or what's called rapeseeds.

00:19:37.530 --> 00:19:39.000 align:middle line:90%
These are like mustard seed.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:42.250 align:middle line:84%
They're yellow flowers,
very attractive.

00:19:42.250 --> 00:19:49.250 align:middle line:84%
We could extract some 2,000 to
3,000 kilograms per acre of oil

00:19:49.250 --> 00:19:52.220 align:middle line:84%
from these plants, and we could
feed the rest to the animals.

00:19:52.220 --> 00:19:56.520 align:middle line:84%
The animals would still
eat the residue of that.

00:19:56.520 --> 00:20:00.010 align:middle line:84%
Canola oil, and make
it into biodiesel.

00:20:00.010 --> 00:20:04.010 align:middle line:84%
We also breakthrough
technologies now using plasma

00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:07.440 align:middle line:84%
plugs, plasma spark
plugs, where we are now

00:20:07.440 --> 00:20:10.880 align:middle line:84%
running micro turbines or
rotary engine turbines, which

00:20:10.880 --> 00:20:15.700 align:middle line:84%
only have one moving
part and have no valves,

00:20:15.700 --> 00:20:23.370 align:middle line:84%
where we can run the engine
on 60% water and 40% alcohol.

00:20:23.370 --> 00:20:28.020 align:middle line:84%
And we're actually making the
hydrogen inside the engine,

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:31.080 align:middle line:90%
and then combusting it.

00:20:31.080 --> 00:20:33.590 align:middle line:84%
>>You said this is
a micro generator?

00:20:33.590 --> 00:20:34.975 align:middle line:90%
>>Micro generator.

00:20:34.975 --> 00:20:35.850 align:middle line:90%
Very, very important.

00:20:35.850 --> 00:20:39.505 align:middle line:84%
>>Give us an example of the
scale of this micro generation

00:20:39.505 --> 00:20:45.430 align:middle line:84%
unit, and what its output
is in practical terms.

00:20:45.430 --> 00:20:46.510 align:middle line:90%
>>Sure.

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:50.440 align:middle line:90%
It's basically a rotary engine.

00:20:50.440 --> 00:20:53.490 align:middle line:84%
It has no pistons and
has a continuing rotating

00:20:53.490 --> 00:20:56.250 align:middle line:90%
Lundell in the center.

00:20:56.250 --> 00:21:00.360 align:middle line:84%
And the engine is
about 50 horsepower.

00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:03.430 align:middle line:84%
And attached to it
with a direct drive,

00:21:03.430 --> 00:21:06.360 align:middle line:84%
one shaft, one
piece of rotation,

00:21:06.360 --> 00:21:14.550 align:middle line:84%
is a 35-kilowatt generator using
neodymium magnets from China.

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:19.810 align:middle line:84%
So these are very high-density
magnetic generators.

00:21:19.810 --> 00:21:23.630 align:middle line:84%
The entire package is
about two cubic feet.

00:21:23.630 --> 00:21:26.150 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if you've ever
seen a 35-kilowatt generator,

00:21:26.150 --> 00:21:28.490 align:middle line:90%
but it's as big as a room.

00:21:28.490 --> 00:21:30.010 align:middle line:84%
So it's all been
miniaturized down

00:21:30.010 --> 00:21:32.250 align:middle line:84%
into this really
tight little package,

00:21:32.250 --> 00:21:35.110 align:middle line:84%
and these are basically
the auxiliary power units

00:21:35.110 --> 00:21:36.889 align:middle line:84%
for the future
hybrid electric cars,

00:21:36.889 --> 00:21:38.680 align:middle line:84%
once we go industrial
with hybrid electric.

00:21:38.680 --> 00:21:41.690 align:middle line:90%


00:21:41.690 --> 00:21:43.879 align:middle line:84%
>>What's their
application right now?

00:21:43.879 --> 00:21:45.420 align:middle line:84%
What would they
power-- what are they

00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:49.980 align:middle line:84%
capable of powering in the
sense of our domestic lives?

00:21:49.980 --> 00:21:54.220 align:middle line:84%
>>Well, 35 kilowatts,
you know, a typical house

00:21:54.220 --> 00:21:58.310 align:middle line:84%
uses about 20 kilowatt
hours per day.

00:21:58.310 --> 00:22:00.540 align:middle line:84%
So with this
running, let's say it

00:22:00.540 --> 00:22:05.980 align:middle line:84%
runs for eight
hours, that would be

00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:10.870 align:middle line:84%
around-- it could
power 10 houses.

00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:14.250 align:middle line:84%
And the fuel would be renewable
in that we can grow the fuel.

00:22:14.250 --> 00:22:16.050 align:middle line:84%
This is not fossil
fuel we're burning.

00:22:16.050 --> 00:22:20.490 align:middle line:84%
This is either alcohol we have
made from biomass or biodiesel

00:22:20.490 --> 00:22:22.070 align:middle line:90%
that we have grown.

00:22:22.070 --> 00:22:26.980 align:middle line:84%
>>So, in essence, what would
the cost be per kilowatt hour

00:22:26.980 --> 00:22:29.135 align:middle line:84%
compared to what we're
paying right now?

00:22:29.135 --> 00:22:31.310 align:middle line:84%
I'm just trying to
get a real, down home

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:35.430 align:middle line:84%
look at what this means in
this tiny little two cubic foot

00:22:35.430 --> 00:22:37.370 align:middle line:90%
device.

00:22:37.370 --> 00:22:41.620 align:middle line:84%
>>The cost would be
certainly probably

00:22:41.620 --> 00:22:44.760 align:middle line:90%
on the level of a wind machine.

00:22:44.760 --> 00:22:47.110 align:middle line:84%
A wind machine, the
capital cost right now

00:22:47.110 --> 00:22:50.130 align:middle line:90%
is $1 a watt for large turbines.

00:22:50.130 --> 00:22:55.580 align:middle line:84%
It's more like $2 a watt
for smaller scale machines.

00:22:55.580 --> 00:23:01.770 align:middle line:84%
So let's say you wanted a
10,000 watt wind machine.

00:23:01.770 --> 00:23:04.230 align:middle line:90%
That would cost around $20,000.

00:23:04.230 --> 00:23:06.445 align:middle line:90%
>>Mm-hm.

00:23:06.445 --> 00:23:13.620 align:middle line:84%
>>A 35-kilowatt device as
I'm talking about this micro

00:23:13.620 --> 00:23:21.140 align:middle line:84%
turbine, would be probably
on the level of $0.50 a watt.

00:23:21.140 --> 00:23:23.400 align:middle line:84%
The beauty of the
renewables, of course,

00:23:23.400 --> 00:23:28.880 align:middle line:84%
is that the device costs money,
but there's no fuel cost.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:31.210 align:middle line:84%
With the micro turbine,
there's some fuel costs.

00:23:31.210 --> 00:23:34.530 align:middle line:84%
But certainly affordable,
very affordable.

00:23:34.530 --> 00:23:39.030 align:middle line:84%
We just need to
manufacture these now.

00:23:39.030 --> 00:23:40.650 align:middle line:84%
>>And that technology
already exists?

00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:43.210 align:middle line:84%
The patents are there and
this is tried and true?

00:23:43.210 --> 00:23:45.020 align:middle line:90%
>>Yes.

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:48.206 align:middle line:84%
>>This has huge applications
then for rural areas

00:23:48.206 --> 00:23:50.390 align:middle line:84%
in particular, it
would sound like.

00:23:50.390 --> 00:23:51.670 align:middle line:90%
>>Exactly.

00:23:51.670 --> 00:23:55.630 align:middle line:84%
One of the-- I'll get
back to your question

00:23:55.630 --> 00:24:00.330 align:middle line:84%
about the other
sources of power,

00:24:00.330 --> 00:24:04.030 align:middle line:84%
but what's basically happened
is the paradigm shift

00:24:04.030 --> 00:24:07.325 align:middle line:90%
is this, as far as renewables.

00:24:07.325 --> 00:24:09.860 align:middle line:84%
And it's comparable
to the internet.

00:24:09.860 --> 00:24:14.250 align:middle line:84%
The internet is a very unique
communications technology

00:24:14.250 --> 00:24:19.220 align:middle line:84%
in that it's now possible to
have two-way communication.

00:24:19.220 --> 00:24:20.690 align:middle line:84%
The previous form
of communication

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:22.290 align:middle line:84%
was de facto
communication where you'd

00:24:22.290 --> 00:24:25.500 align:middle line:84%
have a transmitter
that would send out

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:28.010 align:middle line:84%
the information via
television or whatever,

00:24:28.010 --> 00:24:30.300 align:middle line:84%
and then everybody
would be a receiver.

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:32.590 align:middle line:90%
There was no way to talk back.

00:24:32.590 --> 00:24:35.980 align:middle line:84%
And so in the internet,
you have what's

00:24:35.980 --> 00:24:38.540 align:middle line:84%
called an asynchronous
adapter, which

00:24:38.540 --> 00:24:43.210 align:middle line:84%
allows for two-way
communication protocol.

00:24:43.210 --> 00:24:45.010 align:middle line:84%
Well, in the energy
field, we have

00:24:45.010 --> 00:24:47.540 align:middle line:90%
the same type of technology.

00:24:47.540 --> 00:24:49.850 align:middle line:84%
The previous paradigm
was that energy

00:24:49.850 --> 00:24:52.850 align:middle line:84%
was produced in a
centralized power plant

00:24:52.850 --> 00:24:57.050 align:middle line:84%
and then sent out to the
customers through the grid.

00:24:57.050 --> 00:25:00.920 align:middle line:84%
Now it's possible for the
extremities of the grid,

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:03.330 align:middle line:84%
for each house, to
power the center.

00:25:03.330 --> 00:25:03.950 align:middle line:90%
>>To feedback.

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:05.160 align:middle line:90%
>>To feedback.

00:25:05.160 --> 00:25:07.416 align:middle line:84%
To send energy back to
the main power plant.

00:25:07.416 --> 00:25:09.840 align:middle line:90%
>>It certainly makes sense.

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:12.840 align:middle line:90%
>>Using synchronous inverters.

00:25:12.840 --> 00:25:15.240 align:middle line:84%
So it's just exactly like
the internet, you know?

00:25:15.240 --> 00:25:19.430 align:middle line:84%
So the future of
energy is not going

00:25:19.430 --> 00:25:25.630 align:middle line:84%
to be more nuclear power
plants, more centralized gas

00:25:25.630 --> 00:25:29.150 align:middle line:84%
and oil-fired power
plants, but millions

00:25:29.150 --> 00:25:34.560 align:middle line:84%
of micro generators
in homes and offices

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:36.630 align:middle line:84%
co-producing energy
with the grid

00:25:36.630 --> 00:25:39.230 align:middle line:84%
and feeding it back,
and getting paid for it.

00:25:39.230 --> 00:25:43.650 align:middle line:84%
>>And it sounds as though
certainly the benefits of this

00:25:43.650 --> 00:25:48.350 align:middle line:90%
would be virtually no pollution.

00:25:48.350 --> 00:25:50.440 align:middle line:90%
>>Certainly.

00:25:50.440 --> 00:25:53.630 align:middle line:84%
The other aspect of this whole--
the business of the whole thing

00:25:53.630 --> 00:25:58.660 align:middle line:84%
is when we do a wind
farm, we basically

00:25:58.660 --> 00:26:01.425 align:middle line:84%
are selling our energy through
a power purchase agreement.

00:26:01.425 --> 00:26:04.450 align:middle line:90%


00:26:04.450 --> 00:26:08.030 align:middle line:84%
You know, in China we're selling
it for $0.07 a kilowatt hour.

00:26:08.030 --> 00:26:10.760 align:middle line:84%
In the Philippines
it's $0.11 a kilowatt.

00:26:10.760 --> 00:26:16.040 align:middle line:84%
In California it's
$0.049 cents a kilowatt.

00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:20.820 align:middle line:84%
This is the value of
our energy as we sell it

00:26:20.820 --> 00:26:24.080 align:middle line:84%
on the wholesale level
back to the power grid.

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:28.820 align:middle line:84%
We also will get paid
through greenhouse credits,

00:26:28.820 --> 00:26:33.490 align:middle line:84%
through green tags, about
$0.018 cents per kilowatt hour.

00:26:33.490 --> 00:26:38.520 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we're going to
get rewarded for sequestering

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:42.290 align:middle line:84%
carbon dioxide,
nitrogen dioxide,

00:26:42.290 --> 00:26:47.860 align:middle line:84%
so that we are receiving
credits for pollution

00:26:47.860 --> 00:26:51.450 align:middle line:84%
that we are not producing
through these technologies.

00:26:51.450 --> 00:26:52.980 align:middle line:84%
And that's a really
important part

00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:54.830 align:middle line:90%
to the story, the green tags.

00:26:54.830 --> 00:26:59.060 align:middle line:84%
>>Very important
part to the story.

00:26:59.060 --> 00:27:01.190 align:middle line:84%
Just maybe quickly
touch on the notion

00:27:01.190 --> 00:27:03.250 align:middle line:84%
of clean water and
desalinization--

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:03.750 align:middle line:90%
>>Yes.

00:27:03.750 --> 00:27:05.958 align:middle line:84%
>>-technology at this point
in time before we go back

00:27:05.958 --> 00:27:07.134 align:middle line:90%
to the larger issue.

00:27:07.134 --> 00:27:07.675 align:middle line:90%
>>Definitely.

00:27:07.675 --> 00:27:10.920 align:middle line:90%


00:27:10.920 --> 00:27:14.700 align:middle line:84%
As we look at the planet,
we have a surprising amount

00:27:14.700 --> 00:27:20.670 align:middle line:84%
of very little fresh
water resources.

00:27:20.670 --> 00:27:23.290 align:middle line:84%
And this has been aggravated
by the fact and the invention

00:27:23.290 --> 00:27:24.380 align:middle line:90%
of the flush toilet.

00:27:24.380 --> 00:27:27.310 align:middle line:84%
So basically, every time
somebody goes to the bathroom,

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:32.400 align:middle line:84%
we are flushing some five
gallons of our drinking water

00:27:32.400 --> 00:27:33.901 align:middle line:90%
to the sewage plant.

00:27:33.901 --> 00:27:35.400 align:middle line:84%
And then we go
through great expense

00:27:35.400 --> 00:27:38.940 align:middle line:84%
to clean up what is a
mistake in the first place.

00:27:38.940 --> 00:27:43.620 align:middle line:84%
We're coming out of an
era where our gasoline has

00:27:43.620 --> 00:27:46.120 align:middle line:84%
been cheaper than drinking
water, quite a bit cheaper

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:47.920 align:middle line:90%
than drinking water.

00:27:47.920 --> 00:27:49.650 align:middle line:84%
And so now we're
at the point where

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:54.600 align:middle line:84%
water may become more precious
than our fossil fuels.

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:59.120 align:middle line:84%
We already have drawn down
the aquifers in the Midwest.

00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:05.120 align:middle line:84%
We need to seriously look
at desalinating seawater.

00:28:05.120 --> 00:28:08.380 align:middle line:84%
We have municipalities
like Littleton, Colorado,

00:28:08.380 --> 00:28:13.770 align:middle line:84%
drinking their sewage water,
which has been cleaned.

00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:15.630 align:middle line:90%
Again, a mistake.

00:28:15.630 --> 00:28:20.440 align:middle line:84%
That's a very costly mistake
to use our drinking supplies.

00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:23.210 align:middle line:84%
And some of the technologies
for desalinating seawater

00:28:23.210 --> 00:28:27.880 align:middle line:84%
have involved osmotic membranes,
and very energy intensive.

00:28:27.880 --> 00:28:30.740 align:middle line:84%
It takes a lot of energy
to do it this way.

00:28:30.740 --> 00:28:35.010 align:middle line:84%
And so now, there are all
kinds of new technologies

00:28:35.010 --> 00:28:36.930 align:middle line:90%
like, for example, ultrasonics.

00:28:36.930 --> 00:28:40.280 align:middle line:84%
The ultrasonic
desalinization of water,

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:44.240 align:middle line:84%
where the salt
crystals are actually

00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:46.510 align:middle line:84%
removed ultrasonically,
they precipitate out.

00:28:46.510 --> 00:28:49.700 align:middle line:90%


00:28:49.700 --> 00:28:53.066 align:middle line:84%
There's now talk about
structured water,

00:28:53.066 --> 00:28:57.500 align:middle line:84%
as a way to really enhance
the quality of water.

00:28:57.500 --> 00:29:00.750 align:middle line:84%
Water is-- we know very
little about water,

00:29:00.750 --> 00:29:04.290 align:middle line:84%
even though about
95% of us is water.

00:29:04.290 --> 00:29:07.790 align:middle line:84%
So these are all
the applications.

00:29:07.790 --> 00:29:11.100 align:middle line:84%
I have been focusing on the
development of renewable energy

00:29:11.100 --> 00:29:15.810 align:middle line:84%
technologies and what really
drives it now, and always has,

00:29:15.810 --> 00:29:17.540 align:middle line:90%
is the application.

00:29:17.540 --> 00:29:20.670 align:middle line:84%
Once we produce energy
in a remote area, wow,

00:29:20.670 --> 00:29:22.620 align:middle line:90%
we can desalinate seawater.

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:28.210 align:middle line:84%
We can pump water, we
can do all those tasks

00:29:28.210 --> 00:29:30.580 align:middle line:84%
that have to be done
that require electricity.

00:29:30.580 --> 00:29:33.460 align:middle line:84%
Electricity is the
preferred form of power.

00:29:33.460 --> 00:29:34.420 align:middle line:90%
It has no entropy.

00:29:34.420 --> 00:29:36.170 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't degrade.

00:29:36.170 --> 00:29:39.070 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't run out of a wire.

00:29:39.070 --> 00:29:43.050 align:middle line:84%
It's the preferred form
of power on the planet.

00:29:43.050 --> 00:29:45.140 align:middle line:90%
>>So what's stopping us then?

00:29:45.140 --> 00:29:47.930 align:middle line:84%
All these technologies
you've talked about,

00:29:47.930 --> 00:29:50.040 align:middle line:84%
save for perhaps
some of the last bits

00:29:50.040 --> 00:29:53.968 align:middle line:84%
on the desalinization,
are already present,

00:29:53.968 --> 00:29:55.092 align:middle line:90%
they're already functional.

00:29:55.092 --> 00:29:57.560 align:middle line:84%
The patents,
[INAUDIBLE] are there.

00:29:57.560 --> 00:29:58.060 align:middle line:90%
>>Mm-hm.

00:29:58.060 --> 00:30:00.710 align:middle line:84%
>>Why are we not
seeing more of this?

00:30:00.710 --> 00:30:03.930 align:middle line:84%
Most of the people watching
this have probably never heard

00:30:03.930 --> 00:30:08.304 align:middle line:84%
of most of it, and certainly
have never seen it in use.

00:30:08.304 --> 00:30:09.080 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:13.380 align:middle line:84%
>>Well, it's the nature of how
our financial entrepreneurial

00:30:13.380 --> 00:30:15.000 align:middle line:90%
system works, you know.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:18.340 align:middle line:84%
I mean, fact one, most of
the innovations on the planet

00:30:18.340 --> 00:30:19.840 align:middle line:84%
are coming from
groups of people,

00:30:19.840 --> 00:30:23.520 align:middle line:84%
anywhere from two
to seven people.

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:25.710 align:middle line:84%
More innovations are
coming from the companies

00:30:25.710 --> 00:30:27.306 align:middle line:84%
of that scale than
large corporations.

00:30:27.306 --> 00:30:30.340 align:middle line:90%


00:30:30.340 --> 00:30:32.760 align:middle line:84%
There's a tremendous
amount of effort

00:30:32.760 --> 00:30:36.860 align:middle line:84%
to wait till a company is
established and has a product,

00:30:36.860 --> 00:30:39.830 align:middle line:84%
and then it's bought
by a larger company.

00:30:39.830 --> 00:30:40.527 align:middle line:90%
That's constant.

00:30:40.527 --> 00:30:41.610 align:middle line:90%
That happens all the time.

00:30:41.610 --> 00:30:42.939 align:middle line:90%
>>What do they do, shelve it?

00:30:42.939 --> 00:30:45.550 align:middle line:90%
Why aren't we seeing it?

00:30:45.550 --> 00:30:48.600 align:middle line:84%
>>It's basically--
it's a market problem.

00:30:48.600 --> 00:30:52.430 align:middle line:84%
You have to demonstrate
that you have a market.

00:30:52.430 --> 00:30:55.220 align:middle line:84%
I mean, first of all, let me
give you a perspective on what

00:30:55.220 --> 00:30:57.580 align:middle line:84%
it takes to develop
a new idea, OK?

00:30:57.580 --> 00:30:59.750 align:middle line:90%
There are millions of new ideas.

00:30:59.750 --> 00:31:05.990 align:middle line:84%
But the difference
between having an idea

00:31:05.990 --> 00:31:08.770 align:middle line:84%
and actually getting it
realized in the world,

00:31:08.770 --> 00:31:13.410 align:middle line:84%
there is a huge gulf,
a no-man's land really,

00:31:13.410 --> 00:31:19.240 align:middle line:84%
between having an idea and then
going to your wife or family

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:21.590 align:middle line:84%
and saying, look, I need
to develop this idea.

00:31:21.590 --> 00:31:23.480 align:middle line:84%
This is going to
change the world.

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:25.070 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to make lots of money.

00:31:25.070 --> 00:31:28.040 align:middle line:84%
So I want to borrow money
from the family to do this.

00:31:28.040 --> 00:31:31.160 align:middle line:90%
I need to create a prototype.

00:31:31.160 --> 00:31:35.489 align:middle line:84%
And then even once the prototype
is created, how are you

00:31:35.489 --> 00:31:36.530 align:middle line:90%
going to get it marketed?

00:31:36.530 --> 00:31:38.550 align:middle line:84%
How are you going
to raise money?

00:31:38.550 --> 00:31:42.570 align:middle line:84%
Most inventors at that
